Restrictions in response to coronavirus
Anguilla’s ports, sea and air are closed for all passenger movements until at least 12:01am (local time) on Tuesday 30 June. This date is kept under constant review and may be extended.
With effect from 17 March all persons who have travelled outside of the Caribbean Region within the previous 14 days will be quarantined for 14 days on arrival. A judgement will be made on arrival by health professionals if this can be self-quarantined or quarantined in a Government run health facility.
The regular ferry service from Marigot Port (French St. Martin) to Blowing Point Ferry Port has been suspended with effect from 19:00 (local time) on 17 March until further notice.
Princess Juliana International Airport on the neighbouring island of Dutch St. Maarten has restricted the entry of incoming visitors from the US, Canada and Europe with effect from Tuesday 17 March.
Regular entry requirements
Visas
British nationals don’t need a visa to enter Anguilla as a visitor, but accommodation must be booked prior to arrival. Visitors will be granted entry for a 3 month period. A work permit is required for any form of employment during your stay
Passport validity
You must hold a valid passport to enter Anguilla. Your passport must have at least 6 months’ validity remaining on your date of entry into Anguilla.
Departure tax
A departure tax payment of US$20 cash per person is payable at the airport when departing Anguilla by air.
Departure tax is payable at the ferry terminal when leaving Anguilla by sea to either French St. Martin or Dutch St. Maarten. The amount you pay is dependent on age, whether you are going on a day trip or leaving Anguilla permanently, and whether you are travelling to St. Martin or St. Maarten. Payment at the ferry terminal can be made by credit card or cash.
